# Windows PowerShell Rules

## String Handling
- Use `@"..."@` for multi-line strings
- Always use `-Encoding UTF8` when writing files
- Avoid backticks for line continuation (hard to read)

## Environment Variables
- Temporary (this session): `$env:VAR = "value"`
- Permanent (user): `[Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable("VAR", "value", "User")`
- Permanent (system): `[Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable("VAR", "value", "Machine")`
- Always document required env vars

## File Operations
- Use `-ErrorAction SilentlyContinue` for optional tools
- Use `Join-Path` for dynamic paths
- If a script generates or edits Gradle/Java build files, follow **Java** rules for those files (path style, layout)—do not duplicate Gradle conventions here
- Be explicit: absolute vs. relative paths

## Error Handling
- Check `$LASTEXITCODE` after Java/Gradle commands
- Use `-ErrorAction` flags appropriately
- Fail fast (exit on first error)
- Document what errors mean

## Example: Calling Gradle
```powershell
gradle build
if ($LASTEXITCODE -ne 0) {
    Write-Error "Build failed"
    exit 1
}
gradle run
```

## Testing Scripts
- Test on PowerShell 5.1 (Windows default) AND PowerShell 7 (Core)
- Document which version minimum